    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Donax sordidus</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_865",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Shell triangular but with extended anterior end and truncated posterior end. Surface smooth other than concentric growth lines and fine oblique ridges at posterior end. Colour white to very pale pinkish internally and externally, externally often with yellowish coating, especially near margin.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_866",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 30 mm shell length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_867",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> False Bay to Eastern Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_868",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Burrows in clean sand on wave-exposed sandy beaches and unlike the related <i>D. serra</i>, which occurs on the same beaches, migrates up and down with the tide, popping out of the sand and allowing the swash to move it to a new location before rapidly re-burying itself using its large, mobile foot. Becomes more common towards eastern part of range. Fast growing and short lived, few individuals surviving more than about 17 months.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_869",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Like almost all bivalves feed by pumping water in via an inhalant siphon, filtering out fine particles though the enlarged gills and then ejecting the filtered water though an exhalent siphon.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_870",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Like almost all bivalves is a broadcast spawner. Spawns twice a year in early summer and early winter and grows rapidly reaching 20 mm within one year.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_871",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Easily confused with juveniles of the wedge clam (or ‘white mussel’) <i>D. serra </i>which occurs in the same beaches. However, that species grows to a much larger size, has course wavy ridges running across the truncated posterior end of the shell and is tinged (often brightly) with purple internally.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_872",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fourth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 156).<br><br>Kilburn, R & Rippey, E (1982). Sea Shells of Southern Africa. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg (p. 189).<br><br>McLachlan, A (1979). Growth and production of <i>Donax sordidus</i> Hanley on an open sandy beach in Algoa Bay. <i>African Zoology</i>, 14(2): 61-66.",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_873",
            "longText": null,
